passages.text: Australia | Communications Services Macquarie Technology
FY25 Result - Hitting An

After several consecutive years EBITDA growth, MAQ expects to experience a temporary pause in FY26, as all three divisions encounter headwinds. MAQ is running out of data centre capacity to sell, and there are still no customer commitments for Phase 1 of IC3 SW, scheduled to come online in Sep- 26. CS&G continues to feel the impact of higher prices from a key technology vendor, while increased competition is putting pressure on the Telecom division.

FY25 result. Revenue of \(369.6m\) and EBITDA of \(113.6m\) are in line with consensus. NPAT of \(34.9m\) is a \(2.5\%\) miss to consensus due to higher D&A. MAQ expects FY26 EBITDA to grow marginally on FY25 ( \(113.6m\) ), materially below consensus of \(120.6m\) .

Not much to sell in Data Centres. At the Macquarie Park DC campus, MAQ has c. \(5\%\) of capacity available for sale ( \(\sim 1MW\) ) before IC3 SuperWest comes online (Phase 1 in Sep'26), implying that DC EBITDA can only grow by c. \(2m\) in FY26. There is no indication of customer commitment to take up the 6MW that will be available in Phase 1 of IC3 SW. In terms of the new DC campus (150 MW in Northern Sydney), the decision to go ahead with the site is still pending a subdivision application, and then the timeframe for the DC to come online can be at least 5 years away. We sense that engagement with any capital partners to fund the development is still very premature.

CS&G managing higher input costs. MAQ is still affected by above- CPI price increases from a US tech vendor, with the impact to moderate by the end of FY26. Although MAQ is finding alternative solutions, it may take a while before customers are willing to change their IT architecture. Rationalisation in IT spending is also a headwind.

Challenges in Telecom. Revenue continues to be under pressure and MAQ expects FY26 Telecom EBITDA to fall by \(4m\) , back to FY23 levels. Cost savings from NBN are being passed on to customers as their contracts roll off. The rise of challenger telcos like ABB and SLC may have increased the competitive intensity in the enterprise space.
Earnings changes. We cut our EBITDA forecasts by \(1\%\) in FY26E and \(2\%\) in FY27E. PT to \(64.

Initially a telecommunications services provider, MAQ has transformed itself today into a leading provider of telecom and cloud services to enterprise and government customers, and as an operator of highly- secure data centres in Sydney and Canberra. The transformation has given MAQ exposure to the secular tailwind of cloud migration, resulting in consistent EBITDA growth since FY15.
However, we expect earnings growth to pause in FY26 due to cost increases in CS&G and long lead time in expanding data centre capacity at IC3 Super West.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

EBITDA growth of \(1.1\%\) in FY26 and \(5.1\%\) in FY27. Long term EBITDA margin of \(35\%\) . Data Centre IT capacity reaches 70MW in FY30 with \(70\%\) billing utilisation. Our PT is A \(64.00\) under this scenario and derived from a blended valuation using DCF and SOTP.

MAQ is able to fully pass through cost increases to customers in CS&G and EBITDA margin expands. MAQ signs commercial agreements with hyperscalers for DC capacity for faster deployment. Our PT is A \(73.00\) under this scenario and derived from a blended valuation using DCF and SOTP.

Increased EBITDA margin pressure from cost increases in CS&G. Delays to IC3 SuperWest build and increased capex requirements. Our PT is A \(54.40\) under this scenario and derived from a blended valuation using DCF and SOTP.
Minimising the environmental impact of new infrastructure, ensuring digital and cyber/data security, reducing data centre operational GHG emissions.

1. Aim to maintain a Macquarie Technology female population of \(26\%\) or greater. 
2. Lowering MAQ data centres Power Usage Efficiency (PUE) 
3. Minimum NPS score of 60

1. What are the goals/what is the strategy for achieving employee, executive and board diversity? 
2. How do you enable energy efficiency in your data centres, and how do you engage with customers to support them in reducing emissions associated with data consumption? 
3. What are you investing in to protect MAQ and your customers data?

1. Contract wins with Enterprise and Government customers. 
2. Growth in Data Centre capacity including new sites. Hyperscale contracts in data centres. 
3. Re-negotiation of contracts in CS&G with US tech vendors and MAQ customers.
Figure 2-MAQ Earnings Revisions

FY25 ResultMAQ's FY25 result was in- line with consensus, though FY26 guidance falls below expectations. Revenue of \(369.6m\) and EBITDA of \(113.6m\) were in line with consensus, while NPAT of \(34.9m\) was a \(2.5\%\) miss due to higher D&A. At the divisional level, segment results are largely in line, though Telecom revenue and EBITDA are \(2\%\) and \(3\%\) below consensus, respectively.
Figure 3-MAQ FY25 Result Summary
Source: Company data, Jefferies

FY26 Outlook is below consensus forecasts- MAQ expect FY26 EBITDA to grow marginally on FY25 ( \(113.6m\)). If we assume \(2\%\) growth, then EBITDA would be \(4\%\) below FY26 cons of \(120.6m\).- D&A is to be in the range of \(55 - 60m\) (cons \(58.7m\)). FY26 Group Capex of \(206 - 234m\) (cons \(197m\)), including \(170 - 190m\) in IC3SW capex.- MAQ's undrawn debt facility of \(450m\) along with cash and deposits of \(62m\) is available to fund the construction of IC3 SuperWest and the likely acquisition of the new data centre campus.

CS&G revenue is expected to grow, though EBITDA will grow at a lesser rate, reflecting a margin decline compared to FY25 \((25\%)\) . Pricing pressure from US tech vendors and increased budget pressure from customers led to optimisation of their tech stack and reduced revenue per customer. MAQ expect these pressures to persist into FY26, with easing towards the end of FY26.

Telecom FY26 EBITDA to be around \(20m\) (cons \(24m\)). Margins are expected to fall to high teens (FY25 \(21.3\%\) ) after NBN pricing reduction is passed onto customers. Traditional voice revenue continues to decline in line with industry.

- Data Centres. No explicit EBITDA guidance, though combining the moderate growth in CS&G EBITDA, a \(\) 4m\(decline in Telecom EBITDA, and a marginal improvement in group EBITDA, minimal improvement is likely (c.\) \ \(2m\) as per above).

Telecom. Revenue of \(112.6m\) fell \(6\%\) YoY and was \(2\%\) below consensus. EBITDA grew \(2\%\) YoY to \(\) 24m\(but was\) 3\%\$ below consensus. The Telecom EBITDA margin expanded 1.6ppts to \(21.3\%\)

The telecom business has been able to benefit from NBN price reductions and hence the uplift in margins in FY24 ( \(21.3\%\) ). However, MAQ noted that the current telecom EBITDA margin of low- twenties is unsustainable, and should sit in the high teens. MAQ will be passing onto customers the NBN price reduction. Legacy voice revenue will also continue to decline with the industry. There are still pockets of strength within the division, including SD- WAN, from which MAQ is seeing good growth. MAQ expect this to be a strong contributor of the telco businesses going forward.

The Telecom segment remains an integral part of MAQ's business due to the strong cash generation it provides for the overall business, and also due to the cross- selling opportunities it drives into both CS&G and Data Centres.

Cloud Services & Government. CS&G revenue grew \(2.4\%\) YoY to \(\) 208.7m\(, and was in line with consensus. EBITDA of\) \ \(53.0m\) added \(4.4\%\) YoY and was \(1.5\%\) ahead of consensus. The CS&G EBITDA margin expanded 0.4ppts to \(25\%\)
The CS&G division remains under pressure from price increases by VMware and a subsequent reduction in customer IT spending as they optimise their tech stacks to reduce the impact of price increases.

MAQ is a top tier partner of VMware (one of six in Australia), and MAQ have noted they will continue working with Broadcomm and providing VMware for some years to come. In saying that, MAQ have also launched an alternative solution that is better priced, and can provide customers with more certainty. Some customers have already migrated off VMware onto a non- VMware platform. MAQ expect the overall pressures from VMware to ease into the back half as customers change platforms and there is less optimisation.

Data Centres. Revenue grew \(22\%\) YoY to \(\) 48.4m\(, and was in line with consensus. EBITDA of\) \ \(36.6m\) grew \(5.6\%\) YoY, and was also in line with consensus. The Data Centre EBITDA margin fell \(3.7\) ppts to \(45.8\%\) due to DC development activities and increased power consumption by hyperscalers. Excluding these, the margin was flat.

IC3 SuperWest construction is running on time and on budget for September 2026 delivery of Phase 1 (6MW). MAQ is running out of its space across its built portfolio, with only \(5\%\) left to sell at its Macquarie Park data centre campus.

In terms of customer contracts for the IC3SW build, the timing will depend on the type of customer and their requirements. Hyperscalers could take risk and sign contracts before construction is complete, while government customers will wait until the construction is complete to assess the risk profile. Beyond the initial 6MW built, IC3SW capacity will drop in line with demand and customer requirements.

Macquarie TechnologyMacquarie Technology Group Ltd. engages in the provision of telecom and hosting services. It operates through the following segments: Cloud Services & Government, Telecom, and Data Centers. The company is headquartered in Sydney, Australia.

We value MAQ using a mix of DCF and SOTP. Our DCF assumptions are WACC of \(8.0\%\) , risk- free rate \(4.5\%\) and equity risk premium \(5.0\%\) . We assume a beta of 1.10 and terminal growth rate of \(4.5\%\) . For our SOTP valuation, we apply 12x EV/EBITDA to the CS&G, 20x to Data Centres, and 6.5x to Telecom.
Upside risks: 1) Faster construction timeline at IC3 Super West, 2) Ability to fully pass cost increases to customers in CS&G, 3) Large contract wins in Telecom.
Downside risks: 1) Construction delays at IC3 SuperWest, 2) Loss of government or enterprise customers; 3) competition lowering hosting prices.
